Title: How to be a Python-Django Developer | Live Webinar by GeeksforGeeks
Comment:
Hey guys, a lot of you asked for resources for getting better at Django, here are a few resources:

Creating scalable apps is more than just Django. You might want to get started with studying concepts around scalability and system design. Scalability usually revolves around the use case you're working on but once you know the basics you'll be able to scale your app.


Here are a few links:
https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCRPMAqdtSgd0Ipeef7iFsKw (for system design basics)
https://simpleisbetterthancomplex.com/
https://www.djangoproject.com/community/blogs/
http://tutorials.jenkov.com/oauth2/index.html


Here are a few topics you should study:
- horizontal vs vertical scaling
- web servers scaling (uWSGI, nGINX)
- database query optimisations
- db index allocation
- async programming with RabbitMQ and celery

Title: Mass for Geeks* with Father Roderick
Comment:
I'm Agnostic ( *not* an Atheist!! ), but I'm a big fan of Father Roderick!

The way he is able to reach out to all of us, without judgement or disdain.
No matter who we are, where we come from, or what we do and do not believe in.

Even unashamedly enjoying parts of modern, popular culture (like Star Wars, Star Trek, The Lord of the Rings and Harry Potter!) and appreciating the similarities to his faith and believes, instead of focusing on the differences and in doing so, reject it completely, as so many religious people do. He recognizes such story-elements as "the battle between good and evil", "the heroes journey", "love qonquers all, "the power of friendship" and "faith" (in ones self, in others and in good winning in the end!).

I greatly admire him for this. It shows his big hart and truly open mind.
In the videos on his channel, he often shows a child-like wonder and enthousiasm.
Proving that he doesn't just say the words (like in this sermon), but also implements them into his life!

It breaks my heart to hear when people within the church-hierarchy are looking down upon him for his You-tube antics and his love for Star Wars, Harry Potter (!) and the like.
They fail to understand how much they could learn from this man.
It is often one of the main reasons why people don't (or no longer) go to church.
Too many proud and vain people, literally looking down on those who come to them for guidance and hope. Instead of acting as if they are above us, Father Roderick feels more "of the people".

This is what resonates with people. If "the Church" wants to invite non-believers to come over to them, they need to be able to communicate in a way that touches people and that speaks to them. Using the similarities between popular culture and religion is certainly one of them.

So to Fther Roderick I say: Keep doing what you're doing!
I love your video's and the way you choose to approach everyone and everything around you.

May the Force be with you.
Live long and prosper!
